== QUESTIONS TO ASK YOUR PROVIDER: THE COMPLETE LIST

The answers to these questions reveal more about your birth experience than any hospital tour or website. You don't need to ask every single question on this list—but going in prepared gives you the information you need to make the right choice.

Bring this list to your interview appointment or prenatal visit. Pay attention not just to what your provider says, but how they say it. Do they seem open, patient, and interested in your questions? Or rushed, dismissive, and annoyed?

=== Philosophy and Approach

These questions get at the core of how your provider thinks about birth. The answers here tell you more than anything else on this list.

_"What is your philosophy about birth?"_
- Good answer: A thoughtful response that balances trust in the process with appropriate medical caution
- Great answer: Mentions supporting women's autonomy, shared decision-making, and individualized care
- Red flag: "Birth is unpredictable, so I just handle whatever comes" (no actual philosophy)

_"How do you feel about birth plans?"_
- Good answer: Welcomes them, sees them as communication tools
- Great answer: Asks to review it together and discuss each point at a prenatal visit
- Red flag: Dismissive ("Birth never goes according to plan") or has never been asked

_"What is your cesarean rate? Your induction rate? Your epidural rate?"_
- Good answer: Knows their numbers and shares them openly. Cesarean rate below 25% for first-time, low-risk mothers.#citation[13] Induction rate around 25% or less.
- Great answer: Breaks down their statistics by risk category and explains what drives their numbers
- Red flag: "I don't know," "I don't track that," or defensive refusal to share

_"Do you view birth as a natural process or a medical event?"_
- Good answer: "It's a natural process that occasionally needs medical support"
- Red flag: "It's a medical event—that's why you're in a hospital"

_"How do you handle it when a patient declines a recommended intervention?"_
- Good answer: "I make sure she understands the risks and benefits, and then I respect her decision"
- Great answer: Mentions informed consent AND informed refusal as patient rights
- Red flag: "That hasn't really come up" or "I wouldn't recommend declining"

_"What's your approach to managing labor for low-risk pregnancies?"_
- Good answer: Watchful waiting, patience, supporting the body's process
- Red flag: Routine interventions described as standard regardless of risk status

_"How do you handle patients who have done a lot of research?"_
- Good answer: Appreciates informed patients, willing to discuss evidence
- Red flag: "Dr. Google isn't helpful" or seems threatened by knowledgeable patients

=== Labor and Delivery Practices

These questions tell you what your actual labor experience will look like.

_"Do you support intermittent monitoring versus continuous fetal monitoring?"_
- Good answer: Uses intermittent monitoring for low-risk patients, continuous only when indicated
- Red flag: "Hospital policy requires continuous monitoring for everyone"

_"What's your policy on eating and drinking during labor?"_
- Good answer: Supports clear liquids and light snacks for low-risk labors
- Red flag: "Nothing by mouth once you're admitted" (outdated practice for low-risk women)

_"Do you support freedom of movement during labor?"_
- Good answer: Encourages walking, position changes, birth ball, hands and knees
- Great answer: Describes specific positions they recommend for different stages
- Red flag: "You'll need to stay in bed for monitoring"

_"How do you feel about water birth or laboring in water?"_
- Good answer: Supports laboring in water and/or water birth if the facility allows
- Red flag: "We don't allow that" without explanation, or dismisses the evidence

_"What positions do you encourage for pushing?"_
- Good answer: Side-lying, squatting, hands and knees, whatever feels right to the mother
- Great answer: "I follow the mother's body and instincts"
- Red flag: "On your back with your legs up" as the only option

_"Do you routinely use Pitocin for augmentation? Under what circumstances?"_
- Good answer: Only when labor has truly stalled, after trying other methods first
- Red flag: "We usually start Pitocin if labor slows down"

_"What's your episiotomy rate?"_
- Good answer: Under 5%, only in true emergencies #citation[14]
- Great answer: "I almost never do them—I use warm compresses, perineal support, and patient pushing"
- Red flag: Rates above 10%, or "I do them to prevent tearing" (this is not supported by evidence)

_"Do you practice delayed cord clamping? For how long?"_
- Good answer: At least one to three minutes, or until the cord stops pulsing #citation[15]
- Great answer: Discusses the evidence for delayed clamping and lets you choose
- Red flag: Immediate clamping as routine, or seems unaware of the evidence

_"Do you support immediate skin-to-skin contact?"_
- Good answer: "Absolutely—baby goes right on your chest"
- Great answer: Describes facilitating skin-to-skin even after cesarean
- Red flag: "We need to weigh and measure the baby first" as routine

_"What is your approach to perineal care during pushing?"_
- Good answer: Warm compresses, perineal massage, guided pushing, allowing the perineum to stretch gradually
- Red flag: No specific techniques mentioned, or "we'll see"

=== Timing and Availability

These questions address practical logistics that can make or break your birth experience.

_"Will you personally be at my delivery?"_
- Good answer: Explains their call schedule honestly and tells you who else might attend
- Red flag: Promises they'll definitely be there (unless it's a very small practice, this is often unrealistic)

_"What happens if you're not available when I go into labor?"_
- Good answer: Explains who covers, offers to introduce you to backup providers, ensures backup shares similar philosophy
- Red flag: "Whoever's on call" with no introduction or discussion of their approach

_"How many other patients might you be attending simultaneously?"_
- Good answer: Honest answer with explanation of how they manage multiple patients
- Red flag: Evasive, or a number that concerns you

_"At what point do you recommend coming to the hospital?"_
- Good answer: Discusses contraction patterns, offers phone guidance, individualizes based on your situation and distance
- Red flag: "Come in right away" (leads to longer hospital stays and more interventions)

_"What are your time limits for labor? For pushing?"_
- Good answer: Flexible, based on how mother and baby are doing rather than the clock
- Great answer: "As long as you and baby are doing well, I'm not watching the clock"
- Red flag: Rigid time limits like "if you haven't delivered in 12 hours" or "one hour of pushing max"

_"Under what circumstances would you recommend induction?"_
- Good answer: Specific medical indications (preeclampsia, post-term at 41-42 weeks with concerning testing, PROM without labor after a reasonable time)
- Red flag: Routine induction at 39 weeks for convenience, scheduling inductions based on the calendar rather than medical need

_"How do you feel about patients going past their due date?"_
- Good answer: Comfortable waiting until 41-42 weeks with appropriate monitoring if mother and baby are healthy
- Red flag: Schedules induction at 39 weeks routinely, or uses scare language about going "overdue"

=== Interventions and Emergencies

These questions reveal how your provider handles the moments that matter most.

_"What's your threshold for recommending a cesarean?"_
- Good answer: Specific clinical situations—true fetal distress, cord prolapse, complete placenta previa, failure to progress after all options exhausted
- Red flag: Vague answers, or a defensive tone suggesting they don't want to discuss it

_"How do you handle 'failure to progress'?"_
- Good answer: Tries position changes, movement, rest, hydration, and time before recommending intervention. Recognizes that labor doesn't follow a textbook timeline.
- Red flag: "If you're not progressing on schedule, we need to intervene"

_"What's your approach to fetal monitoring?"_
- Good answer: Intermittent auscultation for low-risk, continuous only when clinically indicated
- Red flag: Continuous electronic fetal monitoring for all patients regardless of risk

_"Under what circumstances would you break my water (amniotomy)?"_
- Good answer: Discusses risks and benefits, only recommends with clear indication, asks for consent
- Red flag: "I usually break the water to speed things up" as routine

_"Do you support VBAC (vaginal birth after cesarean)?"_
- Good answer: Yes, with appropriate monitoring, and can discuss the evidence with you
- Great answer: Has a good VBAC success rate and is enthusiastic about supporting VBAC candidates
- Red flag: "We don't do VBACs" or "it's too risky" without nuance

_"What are your policies on IV fluids versus hep-lock?"_
- Good answer: Hep-lock (IV access without continuous fluids) for low-risk patients, allowing freedom of movement
- Red flag: Mandatory continuous IV for all patients

_"How do you approach pain management?"_
- Good answer: Respects your choice, supports multiple options including non-pharmacological methods, discusses pros and cons of each
- Red flag: Pushes epidurals or dismisses your preference for unmedicated birth

_"How do you handle shoulder dystocia?"_
- Good answer: Confident, specific description of maneuvers (McRoberts, suprapubic pressure, etc.)
- Red flag: Vague, defensive, or unable to describe their approach

_"What happens if meconium is present in the amniotic fluid?"_
- Good answer: Clear explanation of assessment protocol, when intervention is needed versus watchful waiting
- Red flag: Automatic escalation without assessment

=== Newborn Care

These questions address what happens in those critical first hours after birth.

_"What newborn procedures do you consider essential immediately after birth?"_
- Good answer: Discusses each procedure (vitamin K, eye ointment, hepatitis B vaccine, newborn screening) individually with rationale
- Red flag: "Everything is mandatory" without discussion

_"Can I delay or decline any routine newborn procedures?"_
- Good answer: "Let's discuss each one—I can explain what's recommended and why, and you can make informed decisions"
- Red flag: "No, they're all required" (most procedures can legally be delayed or declined with informed refusal)

_"Do you support delayed bathing for the newborn?"_
- Good answer: Yes, at least 12-24 hours, discusses the benefits of vernix
- Red flag: "We bathe them right away" or unaware of the evidence for delayed bathing

_"What's your policy on nursery versus rooming-in?"_
- Good answer: Supports rooming-in as default, nursery available if mother needs rest
- Red flag: Baby goes to nursery automatically, or rooming-in is discouraged

_"What are your protocols for breastfeeding support in the first hour?"_
- Good answer: Skin-to-skin immediately, baby can self-latch, lactation support available
- Red flag: Baby is taken for procedures before first feeding, or formula offered routinely

_"Under what circumstances would the baby need to be separated from me?"_
- Good answer: Only for medical necessity, and explains what those situations would be
- Red flag: Routine separation for baths, exams, or "observation"

=== Practice Logistics

These practical questions can significantly affect your experience.

_"How many providers are in your practice?"_
- Important context: In a large practice, you may not know who delivers your baby.
- Follow-up: "Will I meet all potential delivery providers before my due date?"

_"Will I see the same provider for all my prenatal appointments?"_
- Best scenario: Consistent provider for continuity of care
- Acceptable: Rotating through a small group where you'll meet everyone
- Less ideal: Large practice where you see whoever is available

==== The Rotating Provider Reality

This is one of the most important practical considerations that many expecting parents don't realize until late in pregnancy: *in many OB practices, you will not get YOUR doctor at delivery.*

_How group practices typically work:_

In most multi-provider OB/GYN practices:
- You rotate through different providers at prenatal appointments so you "meet everyone"
- During labor and delivery, you get whoever is on call that day
- That provider may be someone you've only met once—or never met at all
- Your relationship with your primary OB may have little impact on your actual birth experience

This system exists for practical reasons—babies don't arrive on a convenient schedule, and OBs need coverage. But it's a reality that catches many families off-guard.

_Why this matters:_

Your provider's philosophy, intervention rates, and communication style shape your entire birth experience. If you've carefully chosen an OB with a 15% cesarean rate who supports unmedicated birth—but the OB who happens to be on call when you go into labor has a 35% cesarean rate and routinely recommends induction—you don't get the provider you chose.

_Questions to ask about rotating providers:_

- "How many providers are in your practice, and how does call rotation work?"
- "Will I meet all potential delivery providers during my prenatal care?"
- "Do all providers in the practice share the same birth philosophy and intervention approach?"
- "What are the cesarean rates, induction rates, and intervention rates for each provider?"
- "If I have specific birth preferences, how do I ensure the on-call provider will respect them?"
- "Is there any way to request a specific provider, or is it purely based on who's on call?"

_The continuity-of-care advantage:_

This rotating provider reality is one of the main reasons many families choose midwifery care—particularly CNMs in smaller practices or birth centers. In midwifery models:
- You often see the same midwife (or a small team of 2-3 midwives) for all prenatal appointments
- You build a real relationship with the person who will attend your birth
- Your midwife knows your history, your preferences, and your concerns intimately
- There's continuity from first prenatal visit through delivery and postpartum care

Solo OB practices and small midwifery practices offer similar continuity, but they're increasingly rare.

_If you're in a large practice:_

This doesn't mean you can't have a good experience in a group practice. But it does mean:
- Your written birth plan becomes even more important (it's the consistent communication tool)
- Meeting all the providers matters—ask to rotate through everyone during prenatal visits
- Your doula's role becomes more critical (she's your continuity when providers rotate)
- Research the practice's overall statistics, not just one provider's numbers
- Ask hard questions about practice-wide philosophy and whether all providers truly align

_"What hospital do you deliver at?"_
- Follow-up: Research that hospital's cesarean rate, NICU level, and policies independently
- Follow-up: "What is that hospital's cesarean rate for low-risk first-time mothers?"

_"Do you have a backup plan if the hospital is full?"_
- Some hospitals go on "diversion" when full. Know the plan.

_"What's your after-hours availability for questions?"_
- Good answer: Clear system for reaching a provider with urgent concerns
- Red flag: No process for reaching anyone outside office hours

_"What does your prenatal appointment schedule look like?"_
- Standard is monthly through 28 weeks, every two weeks until 36 weeks, then weekly
- Some midwifery practices offer longer appointments (30-60 minutes vs 10-15 minutes)

_"Do you offer any childbirth education or resources?"_
- Some practices offer classes, recommended reading, or online resources
- This signals investment in patient education

=== Questions Specifically for CNMs

If you're considering a Certified Nurse-Midwife, ask these additional questions:

_"What is your collaborative or consulting physician arrangement?"_
- Every CNM has a relationship with a physician for situations requiring medical or surgical intervention. You want to know who that is, whether you can meet them, and what their philosophy is.

_"Under what circumstances would you transfer my care to an OB?"_
- Good answer: Specific clinical scenarios—severe preeclampsia, need for cesarean, certain complications
- Red flag: Very low threshold for transfer, suggesting they're not comfortable managing normal labor variations

_"Do you have hospital privileges?"_
- If you want a hospital birth, your CNM needs admitting privileges at your chosen hospital
- Some CNMs have privileges at multiple hospitals—ask which ones

_"What's your approach to pain management options?"_
- CNMs can order epidurals and other medications. Ask how they balance supporting unmedicated birth with providing medical pain relief.
- Good answer: Discusses all options, supports your choice, offers non-pharmacological methods first if that's your preference

_"How do you handle situations requiring medication you can prescribe versus those requiring OB consultation?"_
- This tells you where the boundaries of their practice are and how seamlessly they handle complications

_"What does your typical labor support look like? Will you be present throughout?"_
- Hospital-based CNMs may manage multiple patients. Birth center and home birth CNMs typically provide continuous one-on-one care.

_"How does your practice handle after-hours calls and triage?"_
- CNMs often provide more accessible between-visit support than OB practices. Ask about their process.

_"Do you attend VBACs?"_
- Some CNMs support VBAC candidates; others refer to OBs. If this applies to you, ask early.

