== RED FLAGS AND GREEN FLAGS: HOW TO READ YOUR PROVIDER

Knowing the right questions to ask is only half the equation. You also need to know how to interpret what you see and hear.

=== Red Flags to Watch For

These are warning signs that a provider may not respect your autonomy or support your birth preferences. Any one of these deserves attention. Multiple red flags mean it's time to seriously consider switching.

*They dismiss your questions or seem annoyed.*
If a provider sighs, checks the clock, or gives one-word answers when you ask questions, imagine how they'll respond when you're in labor and asking for something specific. Your questions are not a burden—they're your right.

*"We'll see how it goes" without ever discussing philosophy.*
This is a non-answer. Every provider has a philosophy and approach. If they won't share it, they may not want you to know what it is.

*They refuse to share their statistics.*
A provider who doesn't know their cesarean rate, induction rate, or episiotomy rate either isn't tracking outcomes (concerning) or doesn't want you to know (more concerning).

*They emphasize worst-case scenarios.*
"Your baby could die" is sometimes medically appropriate—but if fear-based language is the default, that's a provider who uses fear to control decisions rather than providing balanced information.

*They make you feel stupid for asking questions.*
"Where did you read that?" said with contempt, or "You don't need to worry about that" when you ask about evidence-based practices. You deserve a provider who treats your curiosity as an asset.

*They use fear-based language routinely.*
There's a difference between honest risk communication and weaponizing fear. A good provider discusses risks AND benefits. A fear-based provider only discusses risks of the option they don't want you to choose.

*"You don't need a birth plan."*
Any provider who dismisses birth plans is telling you they don't want to be accountable to your preferences. Birth plans are communication tools—and a good provider welcomes communication.

*They schedule induction for non-medical reasons without discussion.*
"Let's get this baby out" at 39 weeks with no medical indication and no conversation about your preferences is a red flag. Elective induction is your choice, not your provider's convenience.

*They talk about your body negatively.*
Comments about your weight, your age, your pelvis size, or your ability to give birth that feel judgmental rather than clinical.

*They pressure you to make decisions immediately.*
Unless it's a genuine emergency, you have time to ask questions. A provider who says "we need to decide right now" about a non-emergent situation is using pressure, not informed consent.

=== Green Flags to Look For

These are signs you've found a provider who will support you well:

*They take time to answer your questions thoroughly.*
Even in a busy practice, a good provider gives you their full attention during your appointment and doesn't rush through your concerns.

*They share their statistics openly.*
"My cesarean rate for first-time low-risk mothers is about 18%—here's what drives that number." Transparency is a sign of confidence and accountability.

*They use phrases like "in your situation" or "for your pregnancy."*
This signals individualized care rather than one-size-fits-all protocols.

*They discuss risks AND benefits of interventions.*
Every intervention has both. A provider who only discusses the risks of declining or only the benefits of accepting is giving you incomplete information.

*They ask about YOUR goals and preferences.*
"What's important to you for your birth experience?" is a green flag. A provider who asks is a provider who plans to listen.

*They say "let's discuss options" rather than "this is what we do."*
Language matters. "Options" signals shared decision-making. "What we do" signals top-down authority.

*They support informed consent AND informed refusal.*
You have the right to say yes AND the right to say no. A provider who respects both is practicing true informed consent.

*They have a low cesarean rate relative to their peers.*
Numbers don't lie. A provider whose outcomes are better than average is doing something right.

*They seem genuinely glad you're asking questions.*
The best providers light up when patients are engaged. They want informed patients because informed patients have better outcomes.

*They recommend resources and encourage you to learn.*
A provider who suggests books, classes, or evidence-based websites is investing in your knowledge—not threatened by it.

